It is one of his characteristics that, following in9 the steps of his contemporary Antiochus the Academic, he strives to reconcile the different schools of philosophy and to obliterate their antagonism. Thus he not only disregards the distinction between the sceptics of the new Academy and the school of Plato¹⁶, but maintains also that there was no material difference between· the Platonics and Peripatetics²⁷. Even the Stoica he contends, have borrowed all from the Academics and Peripatetics and changed the names only⁹⁸‚ or, even if were· cognize any difference between them- and the Peripatetics, such difference can exercise no influence on special Morality⁹⁰. In other places, however, Cicero points out the distinction between the two schoolsw, without regard to the contradiction in which he thereby involves himself. , Of all the philosophical systems that prevailed at Rome 10

the Epicurean was the one which Cicero most disliked³¹t he is sometimes even unjust to it, and in his attacks upon it exhibits more rhetorical pathos than philosophical argu· ment³'. Thus his choice lay between the Stoic, Peripatetic and Academic schools, the latter of which at that time, having been reformed by Antiochus, sought to reconcile the other two. He finds fault with the Peripatetics because in ¹their theory of the affections they justify fear and anger as natural and do not attempt to eradicate such weaknesses³⁸. In ethics also he was influenced more or less by Antiochus, as the books definitus shew.
